description: {"blocks":[{"key":"7cbnv","text":"This protocol is designed for the design and adaptation of a LAMP primer set in order for it to be used with the QUASR technique. In order to do this, it requires an already designed (and hopefully experimentally validated) LAMP primer set. The steps indicated in this protocol are the ones we follow to adapt a previously validated primer set for their use in LAMP-QUASR reactions. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"apsfn","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8m5ul","text":"QUASR is \"a simple technique that allows closed-tube, target-specific detection, based on the inclusion of a dye-labeled primer that is incorporated into a target-specific amplicon if the target is present. A short, complementary quencher hybridizes to unincorporated primer upon cooling down at the end of the reaction, thereby quenching the fluorescence of any unincorporated primer\" (Ball et al., 2016). ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"84fgr","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"36ejd","text":"Therefore, using QUASR-LAMP allows for specific sequence detection and reduces the false positives often associated with unspecific amplification, and it only requires a minor modification of one of the LAMP reaction primers.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7j9ef","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6cer2","text":"This protocol mostly focuses on the software and criteria we use to decide which primer of the set should be picked, modified with a fluorophore, and used as a template for quencher probe design. Some steps are based on the criteria used by Priye et al. (2017), with several modifications and additions of our own. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"C6512300611F11EDAADC5F9C5F64BECF","height":333,"id":315548,"is_video":false,"legend":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"ico4","text":"Principle of QUASR detection in LAMP or RT-LAMP (Ball et al., 2016)","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}},"mime":"image/png","original_name":"image.png","placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jwe8bmtz7.jpg","source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jwe6bmtz7.jpg","type":1,"webp_placeholder":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jwe7bmtz7.webp","webp_source":"https://s3.amazonaws.com/protocols-files/files/jwe5bmtz7.webp","width":550}}}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"b3eum","text":"In order to choose a primer for QUASR probe design, is important to understand the parameters present in a LAMP primer set. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"af9mn","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fiso8","text":"One way to do this, is by checking the complete set of primers (including full-length FIP and BIP) for self-dimerization and/or cross-dimerization using the Multiple Primer Analyzer tool provided by Thermo Fisher and observing the results for primer dimer formation.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":25,"length":121},{"style":"bold","offset":157,"length":24}],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":157,"length":29}],"data":{}},{"key":"e58pm","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6vla1","text":"The default sensitivity value should be 3, for which few to none dimers should be expected. We recommend changing the sensitivity value to 2 and observe the self-dimers and cross-dimers that form. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"italic","offset":0,"length":196},{"style":"bold","offset":139,"length":1}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"57hlf","text":" ","type":"atomic","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"3uotq","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"D6562E50434511EDA7F349639EF6C285","url":"https://www.thermofisher.com/cl/es/home/brands/thermo-scientific/molecular-biology/molecular-biology-learning-center/molecular-biology-resource-library/thermo-scientific-web-tools/multiple-primer-analyzer.html"}},"1":{"type":"notes","mutability":"IMMUTABLE","data":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"3c45d","text":"When we are designing LAMP primers from scratch, we often use this sensitivity setting and reject any set with long regions of complementarity (over 7 bp) or amplifiable primer dimers (with 4-5 bp of dimerization at the 3' end of one sequence), specifically the ones between FIP, BIP, LF and LB, as they are present in a much higher concentration that F3 or B3 in the reaction.","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"33h15","text":"","type":"unstyled"},{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[{"length":244,"offset":0,"style":"bold"}],"key":"5qsk7","text":"In case the primer set has already been experimentally validated, it is still important to consider these interactions as a guide to see which sequence has less probability to form dimers and, therefore, is most suitable for QUASR modification.","type":"unstyled"}],"entityMap":{}}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"hp5","text":"Choose an individual primer for further QUASR modification. If possible, prefer a FIP or BIP labelled primer, as they are present in a higher concentration in the reaction and therefore produce results with higher contrast.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":81,"length":21}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"771g6","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"aghba","text":"If you have a quenching probe of 11-13 bp, reduce its length by one base pair.
